default2. default              defaultHow do you assure yourself that the recorded crime figures for your area are correct? To what extent can you trust the crime statistics for your area? default&#xa0;default2.1 
default              
defaultLet me explain how I assure myself that recorded crime figures are correct.  As PCC, I have variou
defaults governance methods over crime recording.  
default&#xa0;
default2.1.1
default              
defaultFirstly, I have faith in my force because of the HMIC Inspection Reports, which clearly indicate a good culture of crime recording.
default&#xa0;
default2.1.2
default              
defaultSecondly, I co-chair the Force Performance Board with the 
defaultDeputy 
defaultChief Constable. This Board deals with exception reporting of all crime statistics, and has a selected crime topic each quarter. This allows me to see issues in recording practices, as well as emerging crime trends. 
default&#xa0;
default2.1.3
default              
defaultLastly, I am quite "hands on" wi
defaultth these issues. I am fortunate to be an ex detective. I therefore have a very good grasp of the NCRS, and the role of the Crime Management Unit and the Force Registrar.
default&#xa0;
default2.1.4
default              
defaultI regularly meet with the Force Crime and Incident Registrar. These meetings dr
defaultill down into recording practice, and blockages in recording crime and anti-social behaviour. Issues that become apparent are taken to the Deputy Chief Constable (DCC). I have now increased these meetings to bi-monthly.   
default&#xa0;
default2.1.5
default              
defaultThe DCC meets the Force Cr
defaultime and Incident Registrar monthly, to scrutinise recording practice. I have been impressed with this scrutiny. The DCC personally writes to officers (and their line manager) if a discrepancy in crime recording is found. 
default&#xa0;
default2.1.6
default              
defaultSince the Kent Police HMIC 
defaultinspection, and more notably, since the evidence heard by your Committee recently, the Force and I have now formalised this issue to make governance more accountable and transparent. 
default&#xa0;
default2.1.7
default              
defaultThe meetings between the DCC and Force Registrar are now minuted,
default as are my bi-monthly meetings with them both.   These minutes, and responsibility for governance of Crime Recording now sit under the Ethics Committee set up since my election. The Ethics Committee acts on my behalf and reports to the Audit Committee also
default set up since my election. 
default&#xa0;
default2.1.8
default              
defaultThe public clearly have the right to complain about crime investigation or recording. The Ethics Committee "dip check" police complaints on my behalf.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default              
defaultI am 99% confident that all police interventions are 
defaultrecorded
default as the Command and Control system ensures by default that the officers satisfactorily record an outcome to a police attendance/intervention. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default              
defaultI am slightly less confident that all police interventions are 
defaultcorrectly recorded as crimes
default. 
default 
defaultThis
default is for the following reasons:
default&#xa0;
default2.3.1
default              
defaultThe Command and Control system allows officers to record an incident as an anti-social behaviour incident as well as a crime. This is 
defaultpartly because of the confusing scenario where an incident could be classed as "both
default". This then potentially leads to the double counting of individual incidents as both ASB and crimes.
default2.3.2
default              
defaultI know from my experience as a Crime Manager supervising a Crime Management Centre that the only way to say you are 99% confident in your crime reco
defaultrding statistics is to have every crime checked by an 
defaultindependent scrutiniser. My Force does not do this, because of resource issues. I referred to this in my November submission. However, monthly audits are conducted which are overseen by the Deputy Chief
default Constable. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3.3
default              
defaultIn addition, t
defaulthe Force 
defaultCrime and Incident 
defaultRegistrar 
defaultcarries out
default spot checks, and the Force has recently changed procedures in the Force Control Room to ensure that logs are correctly filed with an outcome.
default&#xa0;
default2.3.4
default              
defaultTo achieve total indepe
defaultndent scrutiny of the crime recording system would mean increasing the Force Registrar team by three full time posts, amounting to a cost of roughly £100,000 pa, no mean feat in the current times of austerity. The Force and I are exploring this at the mome
defaultnt. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3.5
default              
defaultHowever, let us put this in context. The British Crime Survey and EU police crime statistics both show a reduction in crime. There is no doubt in my mind that crime is falling, although there is clear evidence that this fall is starting to leve
defaultl out. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3.6
default              
defaultOne cannot comment on crime recording without raising the unknown factor of non-reporting by the public. This factor must always be considered in the round. 
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default              
defaultIn summary, I would say that I am "reasonably confident" that I can trust the 
defaultcrime statistics in my area. However, as previously stated, one should never be complacent. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultJanuary 2014
